# 2. Real-World Example

Suppose a company stores customer information:

| Customer | Age | City      | Purchases | Active |
| -------- | --: | --------- | --------: | ------ |
| Ali      |  25 | Dubai     |         5 | Yes    |
| Sara     |  30 | Sharjah   |         8 | Yes    |
| Ahmed    |  22 | Dubai     |         2 | No     |
| Fatima   |  35 | Abu Dhabi |        10 | Yes    |

Using normal Python, this could be represented using lists and dictionaries.

```python
customers = [
    {
        "name": "Ali",
        "age": 25,
        "city": "Dubai",
        "purchases": 5,
        "active": True,
    },
    {
        "name": "Sara",
        "age": 30,
        "city": "Sharjah",
        "purchases": 8,
        "active": True,
    },
]
```

This works, but data analysis becomes harder as the dataset grows.

With Pandas:

```python
import pandas as pd

customers = pd.DataFrame(
    {
        "name": ["Ali", "Sara", "Ahmed", "Fatima"],
        "age": [25, 30, 22, 35],
        "city": ["Dubai", "Sharjah", "Dubai", "Abu Dhabi"],
        "purchases": [5, 8, 2, 10],
        "active": [True, True, False, True],
    }
)
```

Now we can calculate the average age:

```python
average_age = customers["age"].mean()
```

Filter active customers:

```python
active_customers = customers[customers["active"]]
```

Group customers by city:

```python
city_summary = customers.groupby("city")["purchases"].sum()
```

Pandas turns tabular-data operations into concise, readable code.

