# 28. Time Complexity

Let:

* (n) = number of rows
* (m) = number of columns

Checking required columns:

[
O(m)
]

Checking missing and duplicate IDs:

[
O(n)
]

Cleaning text columns:

[
O(n)
]

Filling missing values:

[
O(n)
]

Creating calculated columns:

[
O(n)
]

Grouping rows:

[
O(n)
]

Sorting (k) city groups:

[
O(k \log k)
]

Since (k) is normally much smaller than (n), the dominant dataset-processing complexity is approximately:

[
\boxed{O(n)}
]

Sorting can make the full operation:

[
\boxed{O(n + k \log k)}
]

Additional memory is approximately:

[
\boxed{O(n)}
]

because cleaned and enriched DataFrame copies are created.

