# 30. Common Errors

## Selecting a Missing Column

```python
students["marks"]
```

When only `"score"` exists:

```text
KeyError: 'marks'
```

Inspect columns:

```python
print(students.columns.tolist())
```

---

## Using `and` Instead of `&`

Incorrect:

```python
students[
    (students["score"] >= 60)
    and (students["city"] == "Dubai")
]
```

Correct:

```python
students[
    (students["score"] >= 60)
    & (students["city"] == "Dubai")
]
```

---

## Missing Parentheses

Incorrect:

```python
students[
    students["score"] >= 60
    & students["score"] <= 90
]
```

Correct:

```python
students[
    (students["score"] >= 60)
    & (students["score"] <= 90)
]
```

---

## Modifying a Filtered Slice

Problematic:

```python
passing = students[
    students["score"] >= 60
]

passing["status"] = "Passed"
```

This may produce a `SettingWithCopyWarning`.

Safer:

```python
passing = students[
    students["score"] >= 60
].copy()

passing["status"] = "Passed"
```

---

## Wrong Data Type

A numeric column may be loaded as text:

```text
"1000"
"2000"
"invalid"
```

Convert it:

```python
students["score"] = pd.to_numeric(
    students["score"],
    errors="coerce",
)
```

Invalid values become `NaN`.

---

## Dividing by Zero

```python
data["total_spent"] / data["purchases"]
```

Rows with zero purchases can produce infinite or invalid values.

Handle zero before division:

```python
safe_purchases = data["purchases"].replace(
    0,
    pd.NA,
)
```

---

## Accidentally Exporting the Index

```python
data.to_csv("report.csv")
```

This writes the index.

Use:

```python
data.to_csv(
    "report.csv",
    index=False,
)
```

